T1  - EQUILIBRIUM SEARCH AND TAX CREDIT REFORM
AU  - Shephard, Andrew
Y1  - 2017/11/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12245
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1047
EP  - 1088
VL  - 58
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12245
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract An empirical equilibrium job search model with wage posting is developed to analyze the impact of U.K. tax reforms. The model allows for a rich characterization of the labor market, with hours responses, accurate representations of the tax and transfer system, and both worker and firm heterogeneity. The British Working Families' Tax Credit and contemporaneous reforms are predicted to increase employment, with equilibrium effects found to be relatively modest. The model is used to assess the impact of alternative policies, with equilibrium effects shown to become important as the generosity of tax credits is increased.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - COMPETITION IN PUBLIC SCHOOL DISTRICTS: CHARTER SCHOOL ENTRY, STUDENT SORTING, AND SCHOOL INPUT DETERMINATION
AU  - Mehta, Nirav
Y1  - 2017/11/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12246
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1089
EP  - 1116
VL  - 58
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12246
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract This article develops and estimates an equilibrium model of charter school entry, school input choices, and student school choices. The structural model renders a comprehensive and internally consistent picture of treatment effects when there may be general equilibrium effects of school competition. Simulations indicate that the mean effect of charter schools on attendant students is positive and varies widely across locations. The mean spillover effect on public school students is small but positive. Lifting caps on charter schools would more than double entry but reduce gains for attendant students.
ER  - 

